            {
                "s2_paper_id": "6125b46b0a201881675a082d118c0aaaa17f88f6",
                "title": "A Case Study of User Experience on Hand-Gesture Video Games",
                "year": 2018,
                "venue": "IEEE Games Entertainment Media Conference",
                "citation_count": 4,
                "reference_count": 13,
                "abstract": "As motion capture systems become reliable and affordable, hand gestures can be identified in real-time and used in video games as alternative game controls. However, there is not enough studies about user experience using gesture input modality for games. In this work, we perform a case study of hand-gesture video games. We try to answer the question \u201cDo players have a delightful experience when they interact with the game using hand gestures?\u201d. We map intuitive hand gestures to commands and use them to control the movement of game characters. We perform a user study based on User Experience Questionnaires (UEQ). In comparing to all interactive products registered in UEQ study database, our gesture control interface scores in the top 1% range showing that gesture based gaming can provide a high level of user satisfaction.",
